{
  "texts": [
    "This stems directly from the complementarity between LLMs and traditional automated testing techniques.",
    "For unit test generation, this synergy offers a pathway to overcome the inherent limitations of each approach, thereby producing more effective and efficient test suites.",
    "Traditional methods such as search-based software testing (SBST) and symbolic execution excel at systematically exploring the program's state space and achieving high structural coverage, yet they often struggle with complex object instantiation, solving complex path constraints involving external libraries, or generating human-readable tests [133].",
    "Conversely, LLMs possess strong code semantic understanding capabilities, enabling them to generate realistic data, handle complex setup logic, and produce highly readable tests, but they lack the systematic rigor to guarantee comprehensive path exploration.",
    "A more forward-looking direction involves shifting the goal of test generation from verifying correct behavior to diagnosing incorrect behavior."
  ]
}